e in their turn fashioned an equally dissociated Milton--at once unconscious and calculating, heterodox and doctrinaire, heroic and intolerable. Silver argues that, ultimately, these contrary Gods and antithetical Miltons arise from the sense we want to give the speaker's justification, which rather than ratifying our assumptions of meaning and the incoherence they foster, seeks fundamentally to reform them and thus to justify God's ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aGod in literature. 0aIrony in literature. 0aTheology in literature. 0aTheology, DoctrinalzEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aAdiaphorism.  aAllegory.  aAntinomianism.  aArminianism.  aBarfield, Owen.  aBarker, Arthur.  aBurkert, Walter.  aCalvinism.  aCavell, Stanley.  aCurran, Stuart.  aDecorum.  aDelphic dicta.  aDryden, John.  aEmpson, William.  aExodus.  aFallon, Robert.  aFerry, Anne.  aFish, Stanley.  aFletcher, Angus.  aGenesis.  aGospels.  aGrose, Christopher.  aGuillory, John.  aHallyn, Fernand.  aHomer.  aIrony.  aIsaiah.  aJeremiah.  aKahn, Victoria.  aKelley, Maurice.  aLactantius.  aLeib, Michael.  aLoewenstein, David.  aMacIntyre, Alisdair.  aMalleus Maleficarum.  aMcGrath, Alister.  aMonism.  aMontaigne, Michel.  aMuller, Richard.  aMysterium tremendum.  aNiebuhr, Reinhold.  aNostra theologica.  aNussbaum, Martha.  aOtto, Rudoph.  aParable.  aPatristics.  aPatterson, Annabel.  aPhilosophical theism.  aPresbyterianism.  aPutnam, Hillary.  aQuilligan, Maureen.  aSacraments.  aScepticism.  aScripture.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400824113zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400824113423Coveruhttps://www